As it traveled on a driveway around the nonprofit's building on the afternoon of Monday, June 8, 2020, the vehicle was blocked by a parked truck belonging to the We Care Food Pantry Inc..
text:
A truck with the El Shaddai Food Ministry of the Crystal River Church of God
drove up to the Community Food Bank of Citrus County in Homosassa to pick up a
freight of goods.

As it traveled on a driveway around the nonprofit's building on the afternoon
of Monday, June 8, 2020, the vehicle was blocked by a parked truck belonging
to the We Care Food Pantry Inc.

The truck reversed to take another route that loops around the property at
5259 W. Cardinal St., but the truck was stopped there as well by a barricade
of pallets in the road.

A worker with We Care sat in a forklift behind the line of wooden columns,
stacked roughly 3 feet high.

He gave a warm greeting to the truck's crew, people he's met before during
their many deliveries with the community food bank (CFBCC).

A forklift driver with CFBCC appeared from inside the organization's warehouse
to load food onto the ministry's truck, steering around the barriers placed
there at around noon.

CFBCC Executive Director Barbara Sprague walked to We Care's neighboring
building to ask her group's landlord to move the barrier for her client's
truck.

Other vehicles, from semitrailers to pickup trucks hauling trailers, also
began lining up.

We Care's board president, Jeanmarie Dunk, and its founder/vice president,
Diane Toto, agreed to Sprague's request.

After the food ministry's truck was loaded, We Care's forklift driver lifted a
pallet out of its way to pass.

We Care officials said this has to be the new normal for CFBCC until it learns
to abide to its lease and make all its food deliveries at the property's
shared loading dock.

"We're blocking them off; we've had enough." Toto told a Chronicle reporter.
"I hate this drastic option  but why can't they use the loading dock?"

Sprague said We Care will not slow CFBCC from getting between 100,000 and
200,000 pounds of food to roughly 50 community pantries in the area a week.

"We're going to continue to work through this in anyway we can," she said,
after calling the fire marshal to check if We Care's blockades were allowed in
case first responders or evacuees needed to enter or leave the property in
case of an emergency.

Sprague said she's also concerned how the barriers might interrupt possible
food distributions from the Federal Emergency Management Agency, which uses
CFBCC as a supply hub for Citrus, Hernando and Sumter counties if disaster
strikes.

"Those are state and federal mandated missions," Sprague said. "There has to
be a direct connection."

This conflict between We Care and CFBCC over the loading dock and restricted
parking entered Citrus County Civil Court in November 2019, when We Care filed
a lawsuit to evict CFBCC, which has been We Care's tenant and neighbor since
2013.

A lease agreement between the nonprofits was automatically renewed in March
2020 for 10 years, according to CFBCC board member Jewel Lamb, who arrived
June 8 to support Sprague.

Lamb said she sat on We Care's board when it raised funds to purchase and
develop the property before We Care opened its doors there in July 2012.

"It's just a real shame what's going on," she said.

On June 4, 2020, We Care attorney Bill Grant sent CFBCC's lawyers with Foley &
Lardner LLP an email, stating barriers would go up at 12:01 p.m. Monday, June
8, to separate We Care's and CFBCC's buildings.

If the food bank needs access to the loading dock attached to We Care's
building, it can use it between 8 a.m. and noon Mondays, Wednesdays and
Fridays.

If CFBCC needs additional time, its staff must contact We Care to make
arrangements.

"No one is going to impact business," Toto said. "We don't want to impact
business."

Toto and Dunk said they're upset with CFBCC, claiming its vehicles crowd the
entire lot and purposefully block We Care's trucks from moving.

"It's not fair for them to say we're impacting their business when they're
impacting our business," Dunk said.

Sprague said not all the agencies CFBCC feeds under a contract with Feeding
Tampa Bay of Feeding America, have commercial trucks to work with an
industrial loading dock.

"If a car were to back up into that, it would be far too low," she said.

CFBCC attorneys sent a proposal to We Care, offering to have a loading zone
striped on the north side of the food bank's building to better accommodate
smaller vehicles picking up food.

Toto and Dunk said a new loading area would bring more traffic and force CFBCC
to travel farther from its warehouse doors to load a delivery.

"There's no reason why they can't use the loading dock," Dunk said.

Sprague said CFBCC will no longer provide food to We Care after Feeding Tampa
Bay ordered her to stop because of We Care's actions and the food-safety
violations it was cited for on May 21, 2020.

Feeding Tampa Bay could not be reached for comment.

An inspector with the Florida Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services
cited We Care for unsanitary food storage and signs of rats in proximity to
its food pallets.

Toto said contracted cleaners took care of the issues, and We Care is ready
for another inspection later in June.

"We've completed everything on the list," she said. "This was a new problem."
